{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518780"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:07:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:07:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12949"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12949"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.07,0.02,0.74,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5387"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65228"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5387"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12949"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50665"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1227"},{"type":"tags","id":"1366"},{"type":"tags","id":"1558"},{"type":"tags","id":"2137"},{"type":"tags","id":"2380"},{"type":"tags","id":"3516"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9335"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9402"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12986"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16272"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18051"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18253"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65228","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65228"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 36-year-old man is admitted to hospital for transsphenoidal surgery to remove a large, nonfunctioning pituitary macroadenoma. Prior to the operation, he had normal fluid intake and output, and his pituitary panel returned normal results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo days after the surgery, the patient develops polyuria, with an approximate urine output of 4.5 litres within a 24-hour period. He also complains of excessive thirst and has been increasing his fluid intake accordingly. He appears well and alert, though his mucous membranes are dry. His blood pressure is 122/86 mmHg and heart rate 96/min.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory testing reveals:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUrine osmolality: 240 mOsm/kg (500-800)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESerum osmolality: 309 mOsm/kg (275-295)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESerum sodium: 148 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUrine specific gravity: 1.002 (1.010-1.030)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUrinalysis: normal, no glucosuria\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ERandom blood glucose: 7.7 mmol/L (4.0-11.1)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fluid restriction","Hydrocortisone","Furosemide","Desmopressin","Continuous renal replacement therapy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with central diabetes insipidus (DI), a well-recognised complication following transsphenoidal pituitary surgery. The diagnosis is supported by the clinical presentation of polyuria and polydipsia, along with the characteristic laboratory findings of hypernatraemia, elevated serum osmolality (309 mOsm/kg), and inappropriately dilute urine (osmolality 240 mOsm/kg). The normal blood glucose and absence of glucosuria effectively rule out diabetes mellitus as a cause of polyuria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDesmopressin\u003C/strong\u003E is the treatment of choice for central DI. It is a synthetic analogue of vasopressin (antidiuretic hormone) that acts on V2 receptors in the kidney collecting ducts to increase water reabsorption. In post-surgical DI, desmopressin can be administered intranasally, orally, or parenterally, with careful monitoring of fluid status and serum sodium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluid restriction\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate and potentially dangerous in this setting. The patient has appropriate thirst in response to his hyperosmolar state, and restricting fluids could lead to severe dehydration and worsening hypernatraemia. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydrocortisone\u003C/strong\u003E, while often required after pituitary surgery to treat secondary adrenal insufficiency, would not address the underlying vasopressin deficiency. While glucocorticoid replacement may be necessary, it would not improve the patient\u0027s polyuria and hypernatraemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFurosemide\u003C/strong\u003E would be contraindicated as it would exacerbate the patient\u0027s free water losses and worsen the hypernatraemic state. Loop diuretics have no role in the management of diabetes insipidus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuous renal replacement therapy\u003C/strong\u003E would be an unnecessarily invasive intervention for this condition. While it could theoretically help manage fluid and electrolyte status, it would not address the underlying hormone deficiency and would expose the patient to unnecessary risks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPost-surgical diabetes insipidus is often transient, resolving within days to weeks as the posterior pituitary recovers from surgical trauma. However, immediate treatment with desmopressin is necessary to prevent complications of severe dehydration and hypernatraemia. Regular monitoring of fluid balance, urine output, serum sodium, and osmolality is essential during treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Central diabetes insipidus commonly occurs after pituitary surgery and is often transient.","The diagnosis of diabetes insipidus is supported by high serum osmolality with inappropriately low urine osmolality.","Desmopressin is the treatment of choice for central diabetes insipidus."],"references":["Tomkins M, Lawless S, Martin-Grace J, Sherlock M, Thompson CJ. Diagnosis and Management of Central Diabetes Insipidus in Adults. J Clin Endocrinol Metab [Internet]. 2022 Oct [cited 2023 Jun 30];107(10):2701-15. Available from: https://academic.oup.com/jcem/article/107/10/2701/6623615 doi: 10.1210/clinem/dgac381","Garrahy A, Moran C, Thompson CJ. Diagnosis and management of central diabetes insipidus in adults. Clin Endocrinol (Oxf) [Internet]. 2019 Jan [cited 2023 Jun 23];90(1):23-30. Available from: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1111/cen.13866 doi: 10.1111/cen.13866"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50665"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12949"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50665"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T22:11:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T22:12:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5387"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65228"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"